children.name: TypewriterText
children.characters:
The tool generates Unity Prefabs that map to Figma Components,   so anything you make as a component will become a prefab (so long as the component is defined in the same file). Soon we’ll add support for external libraries and definitions.

It also supports nested components/prefabs and applies property overrides!

children.name: TypewriterText
children.characters:
It includes an SDF renderer for dynamically rendering core Figma Shapes (Rectangle, Ellipse and Star), so no need to render out textures! 

It supports fills (Image, Linear gradient, Radial Gradient), strokes and shape tweaks such as rectangle roundedness. There’s still some functionality we need to add though, so not everything works perfectly just yet.

children.name: TypewriterText
children.characters:
It uses TextMeshPro for font rendering (with a modified shader to support rendering outlines outside of the font). It also tries to make your life a bit easier by automatically downloading missing fonts from Google Fonts and generating TextMeshPro assets for you. All the fonts in this file were automatically generated on import. 1-Click!

It also generates material presets to apply text effects like shadow and outline where required.

children.name: TypewriterText
children.characters:
As we want to make prototyping as easy as possible, it will also (optionally) generate the prototyping flow that has been designed in your Figma doc. 

That means you can easily create a walkthrough without writing any code at all. Like this one!

children.name: TypewriterText
children.characters:
Hey! This is a little demo of “Figma Unity Bridge” - a free, open source tool that lets you bring your Figma designs into Unity as native objects. 

All of this demo was created in Figma and imported into Unity with 1-Click! This includes all fonts, bitmaps, shapes, illustrations, Screens and even the links between screens!

The tool was made to make prototyping UI elements quick and easy and take the pain out of bringing Figma designs into Unity. The package is open source and free to download. Check the links below for details or click these buttons to explore the functionality. Contributions to the project are very welcome!

Thanks.
Simon Oliver
